Title: Nobody Wants to Read Your Sh*t: Why That Is And What You Can Do About It
Author: Steven Pressfield
My Review:
"What Nobody Wants to Read Your Shit means is that none of us wants to hear your self-centered, ego-driven, unrefined demands for attention. Why Should we? It's boring. There's nothing in it for us."

To avoid this we need to domesticate our stories with these storytelling skills:

1) Every work must be about something (theme)
2) Every work must have a unique framing device
3) Every work must start with an inciting incident
4) Every work can be divided into the Hook, the Build, and the Payoff.
5) Character must represent something greater than himself
6) The protagonist embodies the theme
7) The antagonist personifies the counter theme (This could be internal to the protagonist)
8) The protagonist and antagonist clash in the climax around the issue of the theme
9) The climax resolves the clash between the theme and the counter-theme

Pressfield's personal account of his life as an ad man, movie scriptwriter, and finally novelist expertly weaves these lessons together and gives you hope that you can apply them to your stories.

Title: The Enchiridion & Discourses of Epictetus
Author: Epictetus
My Review: Epictetus is intensely focused on the best way for you to live your life. Everything you have, your body, your things, and your health are technically only rentals. Be fully aware that these things will leave you. Instead of wishing to keep them forever, only wish for them to happen as they will. Only focus on things that are under your control and be aware of your sphere of influence. Master your habits, your actions, and corresponding reactions. Only then can you attain the freedom that will never leave you.

Title: Dress Your Family in Corduroy and Denim
Author: David Sedaris
My Review:
Sedaris expertly straddles between being an asshole and being that quirky friend that you want to be around. I enjoy his ability to decipher social interactions with deadpan clarity like realizing that asking his sister to clean her apartment is asking her to be an entirely different person. But at the same time, his internal dialogue can be so out of touch that what happens next, while being pretty average, can seem unexpectedly clever.

I think his ability to explain his apparent selfish behavior in such a way that converts you to advocate for his position is a real talent. I get the feeling all his conversations are either about stories or fuel for a new one. At the same time, it must be frustrating having a family member who can decide how everyone will remember you when you're dead but at the same time loves making you look bad.

His stories do have great comedic timing though. I found myself chuckling quite a bit with the unexpected turns. His writing puts such interesting images in your head like, "how do palm readers respond to rubber hands?"

I think if there is anything I'd like to take away from his writing it is his ability to guide his reader through uncomfortable situations that always has a satisfying cathartic release. Unlike me, the guy knows how to end an essay.

Title: Solving the Procrastination Puzzle: A Concise Guide to Strategies for Change
Author: Timothy A. Pychyl
My Review: Ever been running with your chest screaming at you to stop? Your legs are burning. You decide okay, I'll stop when I get to that tree. After some suffering, you get there and you have to decide if you really meant what you said or should you just keep running. "There is another tree actually, I'll stop when I get to that." This process repeats ad infinitum until you get to the destination and decided you're badass because you tricked your puny brain into letting your body work more. That's what I've got to do with my work. If there is anything to take from this, it's that you really are leaving a lot on the table by turning in last-minute work. You could do better.

Title: The 5 Elements of Effective Thinking
Author: Edward B. Burger
My Review:
I thought I freed myself from self-help audiobooks. Apparently not. One thing I hope I remember is that the mathematician approach of solving a simpler problem is often more useful than trying to initially grapple with the complexity of the harder problem.

After reading this book, I think all progress is really just incremental. We like to pretend that using metaphors and moving away from the engineering approach is fresh and exciting. The metaphor that I hear is that "Henry Ford didn't try to make a faster horse." But his increased efficiency was trying to make a better car production line. And maybe cars are just more efficient wheelbarrows?

My main gripe with this genre is that the distilled platitudes are so ethereal. It makes sense that they need examples to ground the thoughts but the stories seem like such post hoc simplifications. Something like: I interviewed these billionaires and they all poop on toilets! So I started pooping on toilets and soon I'll cash in!

While these stories are a nice way to paint the world and motivate the platitudes, I don't think my day to day actions will be greatly influenced by this book. Will I be able to tell you the 5 elements? Sure. Will I be a better person? Probably not.

Title: The Brothers Karamazov
Author: Fyodor Dostoyevsky
My Review: I've tried to read this book off and on for at least 3 years. For the first 500 pages or so the characters are difficult to love and the walls of densely packed text make the pages hard to turn. Then as if by magic you suddenly feel like you're part of the Karamazov family and the pages feel like a home. It turns into one of the greatest novels I've ever read and I really wanted to hate this book. The idea of perpetuating classic books for continuity's sake seems like such a mental shortcut when talking about what books you should read. However, I feel confident in taking this shortcut. You should read this book.

A lot of criticism I've read about this book does seem to misrepresent him in ways that are easy to hate which might explain why he seems so defensive about his ideas. Hopefully, this book will actually make you "antifragile" by forcing you to check some of your assumptions.

I'll read Antifragile next but honestly, the Incerto just seems like his own rehashing of the same book as some form of bet-hedging that one of them will become a best seller.

Title: Journey to the End of the Night
Author: Louis-Ferdinand Céline
Additional Authors: Ralph Manheim, Angela Cismaş, William T. Vollmann
My Review: When everything around you is pitch black, it can be hard to tell if your eyes are open or shut. But the difference is huge. If you keep them shut, you have the comfort of seeing the images on the back of your eyelids. All of it is fictitious. When you stare into the darkness with your eyes open, your fears become indistinguishable from what might be lurking around you. Some of it real and some of it fake. Celine’s journey is terrifying because it shows humanity and doesn’t delude you with niceties. You might find despair in the things around you. I’m not sure I would recommend this book.

Title: Animal Farm
Author: George Orwell
My Review: Animal Farm to me is about shifts in power. Unchecked power will always corrupt, just look at the state of gas station toilets. When we have the opportunity to be ourselves without having to deal with the consequences of our actions, we are disgusting. It is easy to criticize others when you are dealing with the consequences of their actions. But if you get the chance to lead, will you think of others or yourself? Find ways to hold yourself accountable and maybe you won’t become the type of person you despise.

Title: No Calculator, No Problem! Mastering Mental Math
Author: Art Benjamin
My Review: Art Benjamin does an incredible job unlocking mental arithmetic through audiobook format. His voice reminds me of Wallace Shawn from the Princess Bride and I half expected him to say "You fool! You fell for the classic blunder of forgetting to carry the one!" Regardless, the useful information for me didn't really start until an hour in but it ramps up quickly after that. There were several moments where I couldn't help but wonder why arithmetic isn't taught this way. Also, I don't think this a passive read by any means. I couldn't drive my car, pause, do 3 digit division, and resume the audiobook without putting others in danger. I would highly recommend this to anyone that works with numbers and very highly recommend this to any math teacher. It'd make a good gift if you'd like to thank someone who makes numbers less cryptic.

Title: The Power of Habit: Why We Do What We Do in Life and Business
Author: Charles Duhigg
My Review:
The Power of Habit by Charles Duhigg reads like a collection of newspaper articles patch worked together sometimes awkwardly stopping and picking up together. This nested story format can turn into a bit of slog with little payoff. I think Charles Duhigg does a great job of finding compelling stories but I wish the advice was more actionable. Here are the key takeaways I got stripped of their context:
- If you want to make something new seem familiar then sandwich it between familiar things. This was useful in making Outkast Hey ya a big hit.
- With new habits, a cue to remind you that you did it is important. Think biofilm on teeth.
- When confronting a negative habit, look for things that occur before the undesirable habit and try to engineer those from happening.
- Put yourself on the self-exemption list for casinos in your state. It could save you a lot of time and money.
- Look for keystone habits that batch other good habits together. One of the examples used was focusing on safety and causing organizational changes consequentially in culture and feedback.

Title: Winners Take All: The Elite Charade of Changing the World
Author: Anand Giridharadas
My Review:
No one will save you. You need to fight for your representation.

That's a pretty alarming message to hear in a book but Anand Giridharadas is eviscerating billionaires and forcing us to look at the guts. We want to believe that the ultra wealthy have become that way because of their merit. We want to believe that they can make the world better with the same skills that made them wealthy. We want win win situations where there aren't losers and all of us are elevated to a high status. We believe prestigious institutions not only faultless, but also make people superior and can solve unsolvable problems. These are some of the lies this book dispels. I haven't read something that has really made me self-reflect as much as this book.

Next time you hear someone saying they have a new method, widget, or whatever solution to a social problem, listen to hear if someone must change. Listen for the systematic injustices that caused the problem in the first place. Listen for changes that do more than maintain the status quo. After reading this book, I realized that true change requires loss of power.

Title: Educated
Author: Tara Westover
My Review:
Tara has been living an incredible life and shared part of it so clearly I see my own. I think it appeals to so many readers because it takes relatable themes like generational gaps, dysfunctional families, the distortion of our own memories, and dials them up to 11. I was drawn to the experience of pursuing higher education in a family that doesn't. I think this book has gotten a lot of attention because it is an academic rag to riches story. But what really was the point of going to Cambridge for a PhD? What is the value of an education if it isn't to train you to do a job? I think Educated expressed a lot of my discomfort with these topics. How many explanations does it take before someone understands or give up trying to understand?

I get the tired trope that a liberal arts education allows you to evaluate your beliefs and decide for yourself. The alternative being a walking zombie. Playing the roles others have decided for us. However, I don't think Tara is a "better" person than her brother Luke because she chose to pursue an education instead of being a farmhand. We all believe unexamined lies and act irrationally. It's easier to scoff at how Tara was raised to not wash hands or avoid hospitals because these lies are more socially repulsive than our own. Education is worshipped as some kind of super power but in the end Tara became estranged from her family. In her case, education was an escape. For others that might find themselves in Tara's situation, education can be a powerful option for a different life but it's not the only way out. All the same, we wouldn't have this great book to talk about if she stayed at home. Should you read it? Yeah probably.

Title: The Practical Bushcraft Survival Guide: How to Find Food, Water, Shelter & Fire In The Wilderness and Survive
Author: Robbie J. Jones
My Review: An excellent introduction to bushcraft. I listened to an audible audiobook and there were some obvious limitations with teaching bushcraft through audio. It's useful to have general idea of what's contained in the field of bushcraft but it fails when it comes to explaining the complexities of shelter, and fire starting. A diagram would just be easier to follow. Same with the rapid fire descriptions of edible plants and water reservoirs. However, the description of declination with compasses and triangulating landmarks was pretty awesome and I've never thought about it before. Once again, this lean book is a great starting point filled with sage advice.

Title: The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn
Author: Mark Twain
Additional Authors: Guy Cardwell, John Seelye, Walter Trier
My Review:
How do you convince someone to change their mind?

If you’ve ever seen a public debate, you’ve seen two people tightly squeeze to their beliefs. They unearth mountains of evidence and listen carefully only to deploy counterarguments. I have never seen someone change their mind in such a public setting, even though changing your mind with new evidence is an admirable trait. If you’re anything like me, the thinking that shapes your beliefs is secret.

Huckleberry Finn is Mark Twain’s trojan horse. He even starts by saying "Person's attempting to find a moral will be banished". Imagine finding a book on your public library shelves promising adventures. You’ll nuzzle up closely with it in the private nook where your big decisions are made and Mark Twain will do the impossible. He will change your mind. Huck Finn is a relatable character even if you’re not from the countryside. The episodic nature of events on the river seems like such a good example of excellent storytelling. I’m not sure how much writers from tv shows I enjoy take direct inspiration from this book or if it’s just what good writers do. By and by, if you give the book the time it deserves it will change your mind. That could be how you treat dehumanized people in your life. Maybe that means to stop discounting others because their packaging is a bit “too hick”.

I also think the contrivance at the end wasn’t completely out of context for the book. I think Tom Sawyer is Mark Twain pointing fun at the little things we want in a satisfying climax and ending. Even though the happily ever after was provided in the end, the way we got there subverted expectations. Maybe you’ll see how your heart strings are being pulled when you see these cliches in action next time and realize how silly it is and how we are just like Tom Sawyer for wanting it to be that way.

Title: A Guide to the Good Life: The Ancient Art of Stoic Joy
Author: William B. Irvine
My Review:
This book has pulled me a bit out of my existential nihilism and articulated some of the reasons why I have been doing what I have been doing.

Here are my take aways:
The pull of insatiable greed and envy can be lessened with purposeful sacrifice. Intelligence, self-improvement and being well-read are a useless circle-jerk unless you are actually doing something with it. Do your duty with no ulterior motives. Get your ego checked by accepting the insults.

I think the book could be more clear on why stoicism might be a better fit for someone than alternatives like christianity, buddhism, or epicureanism. I want to know how a stoic might actually act differently besides being secular, not meditating, or thinking that virtue goes beyond pleasure. This book as a starting point seems great though and William Irvine does provide a nice bibliography to continue with.

Title: The Sports Gene: Inside the Science of Extraordinary Athletic Performance
Author: David   Epstein
My Review: I was excited to read this after reading David Epstein's recent book Range. If you've ever been curious about training for athletic performance or what separates olympic medalists and great athletes, you should check out this book! It expertly talks about nature vs nurture in a way that leaves you with a greater appreciation for human athletic achievement. The gifts we all have are worth appreciating especially the fact that we all respond to training. Let's find out what we are capable of!

Title: The Rock Warrior's Way: Mental Training for Climbers
Author: Arno Ilgner
My Review: I only wish I started this book earlier. The part about the ultimate goal being increasing personal power and learning and all else being provisional goals was absolute gold for me. The ego is a 1,000 headed beast and will steal your strength. Stay mindful, observe and commit.

Title: A Long Way Gone: Memoirs of a Boy Soldier
Author: Ishmael Beah
My Review: I read this book on the plane after returning back to the United States after visiting Sierra Leone. I was fortunate enough to visit Mattru Jong, Bonthe Island, and Freetown with a friend who is from there. So many details felt inescapably real after seeing the places where events happened in this book. That being said, I'm very happy that I read this book after visiting. I think the scars from the civil war are there if you look for them, but Sierra Leone is so much more than the tragedies that have affected the people who live there. The people who live there are some of the friendliest, optimistic people I have ever met. I've learned that the bare ingredients needed to live a fulfilling and happy life is so much simpler than you would expect. I would highly recommend this book because there are horrors and redemptions that are grander than any fiction I have read. However, please see that there is so much more to Sierra Leone than this. The areas where these events happened are some of the most beautiful I have seen. The people I have met are delightful and deserve to be seen for who they are and not just the events that have happened.

Title: Invisible Man
Author: Ralph Ellison
My Review: The layers of disillusionment run thick in this book. It’s not a happy story but an incredible story. It’s a good reminder to focus on what’s real and that’s very personal. I don’t think others can tell you what’s real. You have to go out and find it yourself.

Title: A Monk's Guide to Happiness: Meditation in the 21st century
Author: Gelong Thubten
My Review: I think dispelling the myths about meditation alone made this book worth reading. The point about returning to focus after following a trail of thoughts is a moment to be celebrated is one of the most important things I got from this book. I still don't understand that if you can "achieve" happiness at every moment, then why would you still have the ambition to do anything at all.

Title: The Autobiography of Malcolm X
Author: Malcolm X
My Review: Malcolm X was a complex person. After reading this book I think people whose views change throughout their life are ironically more reliable and trustworthy. His introspection and development into a brilliant and articulate man is one of the greatest comeback stories I've ran into. Alex Haley created a great depiction of Malcolm X. I read this book to have an idea of a life worth writing an autobiography about. I'd highly recommend it.

Title: Moby-Dick or, the Whale
Author: Herman Melville
Additional Authors: Andrew Delbanco, Tom Quirk, Rockwell Kent
My Review: I didn't know human imagination could find an almost infinite number of gripping details in a labor like whaling. This book does an incredible job writing about incredible events. The madness of Captain Ahab and the funny intelligence of Ishmael are a wonderful contrast. Each crew member feels like they must've been someone Herman Melville actually met. I would definitely recommend this book.

Title: Ulysses
Author: James Joyce
Additional Authors: Morris L. Ernst, Nevzat Erkmen, John M. Woolsey
My Review:
"How was your day?"
I think we've all had to synthesize a few short key points out of the nearly infinite thoughts and observations we have every day. Ulysses for me has been a magnifying glass on the in between moments that we don't tell people about. It celebrates the mundane. If you enjoy seeing master craftsmen doing what they do best then you might find some enjoyment from Ulysses.

Honestly, each chapter is written so differently that they feel like different books. Some are incredibly dense and some are chuckle worthy fart jokes. I think the characters are impossible to completely hate or love and their transient nature just feels like everyday encounters. It is clearly paying homage to Ireland and with that comes a lot of specific references that can be scavenged up and some that feel like they are lost forever. There is so much I feel like I missed and thats okay. Unpacking this book could take a lifetime, but I think it's worth the effort to get through once.

Title: Drawdown: The Most Comprehensive Plan Ever Proposed to Reverse Global Warming
Author: Paul Hawken
My Review: I think this book is a great example of research translated into a way that can inform difficult decisions. I think it puts a lot of the issues we grapple with in perspective because often times it's easy to associate the most talked about problems and solutions being the most important. I do wish they had a nice summary somewhere that had one a person can do on their own realistically to help reverse global warming.

I think Pynchon is an undeniably incredible writer and the points of view can be refreshing but I got more satisfaction from finishing this book than actually reading it.

Title: Predictably Irrational: The Hidden Forces That Shape Our Decisions
Author: Dan Ariely
My Review:
Interventions that take our biases into account seem to work so much better than if we just treated people as reward maximizing machines. Some notable examples are the "Save More Tomorrow" program or the credit card that's limited by budgeting. It's odd how these ideas that would clearly solve issues aren't easy to implement on the customer side.

Another key takeaway for me was the discrepancy of market value and social norms. For example, a lawyer may volunteer time but refuse to do work for a discounted price. Developing social norms in a workplace also appears to motivate hard work better than market value in the first place. This is why places like startups or big companies like Google can justify spending money on their employees so that they'll feel socially invested in the outcomes.
